04821nam a22006735i 9780889209459DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892094597 a10.51644/97808892094592doi  a(DE-B1597)667746  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ770.4b.T87 2002eb 7aSOC0250002bisacsh04a362.761 aTurner, Susan M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSomething to Cry About :bAn Argument against Corporal Punishment of Children in Canada /cSusan M. Turner. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (338 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Childhood and Family in Canada00tFront Matter -- tTable of Contents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tThe Terms of the Corporal Punishment Debate -- tA Very Short History of Moral Philosophy -- tMorality and Culture: When Values Collide -- tPhilosophical Morality: Happiness and Harm -- tHuman Adults and Human Children -- tThe Paradox of Child Protection -- tCorporal Punishment: Its Defenders -- tCorporal Punishment and Special Defences in the Law -- tThe Legal Challenge for Section 43 -- tWhat About Spanking? -- tChild Abuse and Family Statism Revisited -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tAppendix -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy does our society think it is okay to hit children? Almost everyone thinks it is wrong to abuse a child. But many parents and teachers believe it is okay to spank children, rap their knuckles, slap their faces, pull their hair and yank their arms, as long as the punishment does not result in serious injury or death, and is intended to improve a child’s behaviour. Susan M. Turner explores the historical, psychological, sociological and legal foundations of this belief from a philosophical perspective and argues why it should be abandoned. Something to Cry About presents evidence from recent studies showing that all forms of corporal punishment pose significant risks for children and that none improves behaviour in the long term. Dr. Turner also examines Section 43 of the Canadian Criminal Code — a law that protects those who punish children in their care by allowing them to hit the children as long as such punishment is “reasonable,” even though Canadian case law shows that “reasonable” has included breaking a child’s fingers. Turner presents a comprehensive argument in favour of repeal. In Something to Cry About, Turner takes a definite stand, but does so in a way that invites critical dialogue. Her work is the first to set out the debate over corporal punishment in multidisciplinary terms pertinent to Canadian society. She brings together in one place a wide variety of thought and data which can be consulted by all Canadians concerned with the welfare of children.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild abusexCanada. 0aChild abusezCanada. 0aCorporal punishmentxCanada. 0aCorporal punishmentzCanada. 0aDiscipline of children. 0aEnfantsxDisciplinexCanadaxCanada. 0aPunitions corporellesxCanada. 0aViolence envers les enfantsxCanada. 4aLaw. 4aLaw: Child Advocacy. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitical Science. 4aPolitical Science: Social Policy. 4aSocial Science: Social Work. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920945940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889209459423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889209459/original  